(PISA_2012 Data Visualization)¶

by (Mostafa Massoud)¶

Understand The Data¶

PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. It is not a conventional school test. Rather than examining how well students have learned the school curriculum, it looks at how well prepared they are for life beyond school.

Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science representing about 28 million 15-year-olds globally. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

With the original data comes a second csv file which contain small describtion for the data columns

#Choosen columns
cat_cols = ['CNT','ST08Q01','ST09Q01','ST13Q01','ST17Q01','ST29Q04']

Befor we continue forward I think it's important to understand plausible values, as I won't invistigate plausible value individually. %%time
def higher_edu(row):
    '''
    Returns the heighest education level for both parent
    
    '''
    if row['father_edu'] is np.nan or row['mother_edu'] is np.nan:
        return np.nan
    edu_order = {'lvl 0':1, 'lvl 1':1, 'lvl 2':2, 'lvl 3A':3,'lvl (3B,3C)':4}
    father_education = row['father_edu']
    mother_education = row['mother_edu']
    
    if mother_education == father_education:
        return mother_education
    elif edu_order[father_education] > edu_order[mother_education]:
        return father_education
    else:
        return mother_education

analysis_df['higher_edu'] = analysis_df.apply(lambda x : higher_edu(x),axis=1)

analysis_df['higher_edu'] = analysis_df['higher_edu'].astype(pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ['lvl 0', 'lvl 1', 'lvl 2', 'lvl 3A', 'lvl (3B,3C)']))

def cat_facet_distibution(col,dataframe,ylim):
    '''
    Plotting for each different value in catagorical column boxplot and Histogram plot for pvmath_mean column
    '''
    values = {
        'mother_edu': [['lvl 0', 'lvl 1', 'lvl 2', 'lvl 3A', 'lvl (3B,3C)'],'Education Level for Parents'],
        'father_edu': [['lvl 0', 'lvl 1', 'lvl 2', 'lvl 3A', 'lvl (3B,3C)'],'Education Level for Parents'],
        'higher_edu': [['lvl 0', 'lvl 1', 'lvl 2', 'lvl 3A', 'lvl (3B,3C)'],'Education Level for Parents'],
        'enjoy_math': [['Strongly disagree', 'Disagree', 'Agree', 'Strongly agree'],'Maths Enjoyment'],
        'late':       [['5 or more', '3-4 Times', '1-2 Times','Never'],'Times Being Late to School'],
        'skip_day':   [['5 or more', '3-4 Times', '1-2 Times', 'Never'],'Times School Day Skipping']
             }
    
    column_values = values[col][0]
    #plotting ditribution of pvmath_mean with education level
    fig,axes = plt.subplots(2,len(column_values),figsize=(18,8),constrained_layout=True)
    fig.suptitle(f'Distribution of PVMATH Values with Different {values[col][1]}',size=15)
    
    
    for i in range(len(column_values)):
        #Getting plotting data and axes
        lvl = column_values[i]
        df = dataframe[dataframe[col]==lvl]
        ax1 = axes[0][i]
        ax2 = axes[1][i]
        #Boxplot
        sns.boxplot(x='pvmath_mean',data=df,ax=ax1)
        ax1.set_title(f'{lvl} PVMATH Values Boxplt \nWith Mean = {round(df["pvmath_mean"].mean(),2)}')
        ax1.set_xlabel('')
        #Histogram
        sns.histplot(x='pvmath_mean',data=df,ax=ax2)
        ax2.set_title(f'{lvl} PVMATH Values Histogram')
        ax2.set_ylim([0,ylim])
        ax2.set_xlabel('')

def remove_outlier(df,col):
    '''
    Return DataFrame "df" with now outlier in column "col"
    '''
    Q1 = class_period[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = class_period[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    return df[~((df[col] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) |(df[col] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)))].copy()
    
def multi_regplot_facet(df,cat_col,num_col,height=4,aspect=0.8):
    '''
    Creating FacetGrid for catagorical column with numerical column from DataFrame
    And mapping regplot to the FacetGrid.
    '''
    facetgrid = sns.FacetGrid(data=df, col=cat_col, height=height, aspect=aspect)
    facetgrid.map(sns.regplot,num_col,'pvmath_mean',x_jitter=0.07,scatter_kws={'alpha':1/10})
    
def multi_scatter_facet(df,cat_col,num_col,height=4,aspect=0.8):
    '''
    Creating FacetGrid for catagorical column with numerical column from DataFrame
    And mapping scatterplot to the FacetGrid.
    '''
    facetgrid = sns.FacetGrid(data=df, col=cat_col, height=height, aspect=aspect)
    facetgrid.map(sns.scatterplot,num_col,'pvmath_mean')

With more investigation about relation of late column with skip_day column and mean value for PVMATH the investigation strengthened the previous relation that late and skip day impact pvmath score and now we can see that both columns can also affect PVMATH value differently, and confirming that skipping school day has more impact on PVMATH value than just being late.
